Trilaciclib RS regression — asterisk footnote for salt/base conversion not parsed.

Bug: Excel shows Trilaciclib 2HCl qty = 349* with footnote "349 mg dihydrochloride
= 300 mg base". Pipeline uses 349 as label strength for multiplier calc.
Multiplier becomes 432/349 = 1.237822 (wrong). Approved = 432/300 = 1.44.

Root cause: asterisk footnote not detected/parsed for salt/base conversion.

Fix in single_strength_unit_composition mode Excel parser:

1. Detect asterisk footnote pattern in Excel:
- Look for ingredient rows where Qty. cell contains "X*", "X**", "X#", or 
other footnote markers
- Search Excel below composition table for matching footnote text
- Also check for salt suffix in ingredient name: 2HCl, HCl, dihydrochloride,
hydrochloride, sulfate, tartrate, mesylate, tosylate, besylate, phosphate,
acetate, citrate, sodium, potassium
- Pattern in footnote text: "X mg of [salt] is equivalent to Y mg [base]"
or "X mg of [salt] equals Y mg [base]" or "as [base name]" or "provided as
[salt form]" or "[X] mg [salt] contains [Y] mg [base]"

2. When asterisk + footnote pattern detected, show UI dialog before MDD input:
- "Salt-form API detected: [ingredient name]"
- "Formulation weight (salt): [detected value] mg/vial (from Excel)"
- "Label strength (base): [___] mg/vial" (asks user, no default)
- Auto-compute: salt/base ratio for internal use
- Show hint: "Common salt/base conversions: HCl adds ~36.5 g/mol, 
dihydrochloride adds ~73 g/mol, sulfate adds ~98 g/mol"

3. Multiplier calculation for salt-form APIs:
multiplier = MDD / label_strength_base
NOT MDD / salt_weight

Trilaciclib: multiplier = 432 / 300 = 1.44 ✓
NOT 432 / 349 = 1.237822 ✗

4. Component amount calculation:
API row: amount_in_max_dose = salt_weight × multiplier
(salt carries solvent burden — vendor annexures test the salt form)
Trilaciclib: 349 × 1.44 = 502.56 mg
Excipient rows: amount_in_max_dose = qty × multiplier
Mannitol: 300 × 1.44 = 432 mg
Drug product mass (solid dosage): sum of non-q.s. amounts
Trilaciclib total: 502.56 + 432 + 108.86 = 1043.42 mg = 1.043 g

5. Salt/base vs Overage distinction:
Salt/base: asterisk footnote mentions "equivalent to X mg base" or similar
→ multiplier uses BASE weight, API amount uses SALT weight
Overage: asterisk footnote mentions "10% overage", "5% overage", etc.
→ multiplier uses EFFECTIVE strength (nominal), API amount uses NOMINAL
Both patterns detected via same asterisk but handled by parsing footnote 
content

6. Metadata display for salt-form products:
- Strength field: label base value ("300 mg/vial") NOT salt value
- Add footnote to strength: "* [salt weight] mg [salt name] equivalent to 
[base weight] mg [base name]"
- Do NOT display salt weight as strength

7. Detection rules for asterisk footnote in Excel:
a. Scan cells below composition table for text starting with "*"
b. Also scan cells in "Function" column continuation, note column, notes 
section
c. Also scan same sheet, adjacent sheet, or "Notes" sheet if present
d. Match footnote content against salt/base or overage patterns

8. If footnote detected but conversion factor cannot be parsed automatically:
- Show user warning: "Asterisk footnote detected for [ingredient] but 
conversion factor could not be parsed. Please enter values manually."
- Prompt for both salt and base weights

Acceptance for Trilaciclib:
- Excel parsed: Trilaciclib 2HCl 349*, footnote "349 mg equivalent to 300 mg base"
- UI shows salt/base dialog: "Salt weight: 349, Label strength (base): 300"
- Multiplier = 432/300 = 1.44 ✓
- Trilaciclib amount in max dose = 349 × 1.44 = 502.56 mg = 0.503 g ✓
- Mannitol amount = 300 × 1.44 = 432 mg = 0.432 g ✓
- Citric acid amount = 75.6 × 1.44 = 108.86 mg = 0.109 g ✓
- Drug Product mass = 502.56 + 432 + 108.86 = 1043.42 mg = 1.043 g ✓
- Strength display: "300 mg/vial" (with footnote about salt equivalent) ✓
- Daily Exposure values match approved TSR:
Methanol: 502.56 × 3000 / 1e6 = 1.509 mg (approved: 1.51) ✓
DCM: 502.56 × 600 / 1e6 = 0.302 mg (approved: 0.30) ✓
Toluene: 502.56 × 890 / 1e6 = 0.448 mg (approved: 0.45) ✓
All others match with same pattern

Do not regress:
- Epinephrine (uses OVERAGE, different footnote content, different handling)
- Esomeprazole (no asterisk, standard multiplier calculation)
- Any product without salt/base or overage indicators

Universal rule. Any product with salt-form API + label footnote should now 
work identically to Trilaciclib.
